    "description": "Narrow rectangular fabric, hemmed at both ends with red stitching, striped in white and two shades of indigo.",
    "justification": "This African cloth, called akwa-mmiri (literally \u201ccloth of water\"), is made from locally grown, hand-spun cotton yarns, hand-dyed in two shades of indigo blue. These blues, plus white, are used to form irregular stripes down the center of the narrow panel. Historically associated with the war dance, today the cloth may be worn for this dance as well as for special festivals such as Eloso (the New Year festival celebrated once every two years in September), the New Yam Festival, or for the funeral of an important man. \nFor the war dance, the cloth can be worn as a loincloth. For modern ceremonial use, it is often worn tied in a single knot at the waist, over a floor length piece of George, a highly-valued fine cotton plaid fabric imported from India. In the funeral context, the cloth is a mark of respect for the deceased, indicating that he was a courageous man and a defender of his community.\nAkwa-mmiri is handed down from the father to the eldest son in a family, often at the time of the death of the father. This type of fabric is still very important and has a high societal value. The akwa-mmiri under consideration for acquisition would be the first example of this type of textile to enter the museum\u2019s collection.",
